This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane.

06:29.860 --> 06:35.020
Science fiction writer Clifford Simac has been publishing almost continuously every year since 1938.

06:35.840 --> 06:38.340
Right, but Simac's first stories were published several years earlier.

06:38.860 --> 06:42.200
Here he explains how his writing career got started and how it was temporarily stopped.

06:43.280 --> 06:47.860
I started my newspaper career in 1929.

06:49.000 --> 06:54.640
And my first short story appeared in, I think, 1931.

06:56.520 --> 07:01.640
And at that time I wrote several other short stories which were published.

07:03.540 --> 07:11.140
And at about that time the magazine, the all magazines, the science fiction magazines and all others

07:11.900 --> 07:15.180
ran at a hard time because the Great Depression came along.

07:17.520 --> 07:21.540
And so there was no market, or practically no market.

07:22.260 --> 07:31.920
So I dropped out and didn't do any more writing any other fiction writing of any kind until I think it was 37 or 38.

07:32.760 --> 07:36.800
And I started writing again because the magazines had come back.

07:37.580 --> 07:41.640
John Campbell had been named editor of a Stelman.

07:42.360 --> 07:46.360
And I felt fairly sure I could sell my work to John Campbell.

07:47.260 --> 07:48.820
So I started then again.

07:49.400 --> 07:58.200
And I think since 1938 to 1939, I think it's 37 or 38.

07:59.080 --> 08:03.900
There was only one year in which none of my work appeared.

08:04.360 --> 08:05.660
There was one year at this point.

08:06.280 --> 08:09.380
And I can't remember which year it was.

08:09.580 --> 08:11.260
And I have no idea why that occurred.

08:22.480 --> 08:28.100
So CIMEC became an early mainstay in John W. Campbell's stable of writers at Astounding Stories.

08:28.560 --> 08:31.020
We asked CIMEC why he thought his work appealed to Campbell.

08:31.660 --> 08:33.640
I've read a lot of John Campbell's work.

08:33.640 --> 08:50.500
And I knew it, John Campbell was a favorite of what we today call hard science fiction.

08:51.540 --> 08:54.720
And I thought that I could write that kind of science fiction.

08:55.560 --> 08:58.840
I did write what amounted to hard science fiction for some years.

08:58.840 --> 09:04.160
And then begin to turn it over to the softer science fiction, such most of which will.

09:05.060 --> 09:07.360
Well, most people write soft science fiction.

09:07.500 --> 09:13.160
They only a few in the old hands and maybe a few new beginners write the hard science fiction today.

09:20.060 --> 09:24.240
During the first few decades he wrote, CIMEC produced short stories almost exclusively.

09:24.840 --> 09:27.320
We asked him to tell us why he stuck to the short story form.

09:28.240 --> 09:33.740
A short story is the training ground for the novelist.

09:34.640 --> 09:41.380
You can learn a lot more from writing a short story than you can write a novel.

09:42.200 --> 09:47.060
It's shorter to write, somewhat easier to write.

09:47.960 --> 09:52.260
You don't have the time invested in a short story to do a novel.

09:52.260 --> 09:59.840
If you spend, as a beginner, probably six months or a year writing a novel,

10:00.060 --> 10:01.940
it fails when that's catastrophic.

10:03.360 --> 10:08.100
But during that same time you could write a half a dozen short stories

10:08.100 --> 10:13.400
and if only one of them sold, why okay, you have made a beginning.

10:14.320 --> 10:23.600
So it's the path that most people take to becoming, to becoming writers or long-going to work.

10:24.460 --> 10:31.760
And that doesn't apply only to the science fiction field but to any literature.

10:32.920 --> 10:35.320
More on Clifford CIMEC on our next show.

10:42.420 --> 10:44.980
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show,

10:45.320 --> 10:47.920
a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association

10:47.920 --> 10:51.060
produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

